




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Impetuous Youngsters and Jaded Old-Timers: Acquiring a Reputation for Learning
AU  - Prendergast, Canice
AU  - Stole, Lars
Y1  - 1996/12/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/262055
DO  - 10.1086/262055
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1105
EP  - 1134
VL  - 104
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper examines individual decision making when decisions reflect on people's ability to learn. We address this problem in the context of a manager making investment decisions on a project over time. We show that in an effort to appear as a fast learner, the manager will exaggerate his own information; but ultimately, he becomes too conservative, being unwilling to change his investments on the basis of new information. Our results arise purely from learning about competence rather than concavity or convexity of the rewards functions. We relate our results to the existing psychology literature concerning cognitive dissonance reduction.
AB  - This paper examines individual decision making when decisions reflect on people's ability to learn. We address this problem in the context of a manager making investment decisions on a project over time. We show that in an effort to appear as a fast learner, the manager will exaggerate his own information; but ultimately, he becomes too conservative, being unwilling to change his investments on the basis of new information. Our results arise purely from learning about competence rather than concavity or convexity of the rewards functions. We relate our results to the existing psychology literature concerning cognitive dissonance reduction.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/262055
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/262055
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Monetary Explanation of the Equity Premium, Term Premium, and Risk-Free Rate Puzzles
AU  - Bansal, Ravi
AU  - Coleman, Wilbur John
Y1  - 1996/12/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/262056
DO  - 10.1086/262056
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1135
EP  - 1171
VL  - 104
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper develops and estimates a monetary model that offers an explanation of some puzzling features of observed returns on equities and default-free bonds. The key feature of the model is that some assets other than money play a special role in facilitating transactions, which affects the rate of return that they offer. The model is capable of producing a low risk-free rate, a high equity premium, and an average positive relationship between maturity and term premium for default-free bonds. The model's implications for the joint distribution of asset returns, velocity, inflation, money growth, and consumption growth are also compared to the behavior of these variables in the U.S. economy.
AB  - This paper develops and estimates a monetary model that offers an explanation of some puzzling features of observed returns on equities and default-free bonds. The key feature of the model is that some assets other than money play a special role in facilitating transactions, which affects the rate of return that they offer. The model is capable of producing a low risk-free rate, a high equity premium, and an average positive relationship between maturity and term premium for default-free bonds. The model's implications for the joint distribution of asset returns, velocity, inflation, money growth, and consumption growth are also compared to the behavior of these variables in the U.S. economy.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/262056
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/262056
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Credit, Incentives, and Reputation: A Hedonic Analysis of Contractual Wage Profiles
AU  - Brandt, Loren
AU  - Hosios, Arthur J.
Y1  - 1996/12/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/262057
DO  - 10.1086/262057
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1172
EP  - 1226
VL  - 104
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - A hedonic analysis of principal-agent employment contracts is developed in which workers and employers exchange labor services and contractual payment patterns. Within this framework, tests of alternative hypotheses are formulated and applied to contract data from a unique household-level survey of economic activity in rural China in 1935. The results indicate that credit market constraints motivated workers' and employers' contract choices, that shirking by workers rather than by employers was the dominant incentive issue, that reputational concerns rather than threats of termination were the key worker-disciplining device, and, finally, that the contract's third party acted as an enforcement device rather than as a matchmaker. Subject to the availability of matched agent-principal data, this structural approach to modeling agency relationships can also be used in contemporary settings.
AB  - A hedonic analysis of principal-agent employment contracts is developed in which workers and employers exchange labor services and contractual payment patterns. Within this framework, tests of alternative hypotheses are formulated and applied to contract data from a unique household-level survey of economic activity in rural China in 1935. The results indicate that credit market constraints motivated workers' and employers' contract choices, that shirking by workers rather than by employers was the dominant incentive issue, that reputational concerns rather than threats of termination were the key worker-disciplining device, and, finally, that the contract's third party acted as an enforcement device rather than as a matchmaker. Subject to the availability of matched agent-principal data, this structural approach to modeling agency relationships can also be used in contemporary settings.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/262057
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/262057
Y2  - 2024/03/22
